  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Forty-seven percent. Sit with that number for a moment. Not a 12% nudge, not a statistically marginal effect that requires a forest plot and a generous squint to appreciate. A 47% reduction in the risk of worsening substance use disorder — from a drug that was designed to lower blood sugar. A physician at a Swedish clinic, reviewing a diabetic patient's chart six months after starting semaglutide, notices that the patient's alcohol use has dropped. The psychiatric notes are quieter. The crisis calls have stopped. Nothing in the prescription explained this. Nothing in the mechanism, as it was originally understood, predicted it. And yet there it is, replicated across 95,490 people in a national registry, in a study published in <em>The Lancet Psychiatry</em> on March 18, 2026.</p>
  <p>The question that finding forces is not a comfortable one. What does it mean when a metabolic drug — one approved for glycemic control, later for obesity — outperforms dedicated psychiatric medications on psychiatric outcomes? Either we have stumbled onto something extraordinary about this class of drugs, or we have stumbled onto something deeply uncomfortable about how psychiatry has been conceptualizing the disorders it treats. The honest answer, as this piece will argue, is probably both.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-study" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Methodological Story Nobody Is Telling Loudly Enough</h2>
  <p>Before the numbers mean anything, the design has to mean something. Most observational studies comparing drug users to non-users are haunted by healthy-user bias: people who take medications consistently tend to be more health-conscious, better resourced, and less sick at baseline than people who don't. That bias can manufacture benefits that don't exist. The Swedish cohort study, led by Markku Lähteenvuo, MD, PhD, of the University of Eastern Finland, used a within-individual design — stratified Cox regression models that compare each person's psychiatric outcomes during periods when they were taking semaglutide against periods when they were not. Same person. Different drug exposure windows. The confounders that live between individuals — socioeconomic status, baseline health, motivation — are largely neutralized, because you're not comparing different people anymore.</p>
  <p>That is a meaningful methodological upgrade. It doesn't make the study causal — Lähteenvuo himself was careful to say "we cannot determine exactly why or how these medications affect mood symptoms" — but it substantially raises the evidentiary floor. The study also ran a head-to-head comparison: semaglutide versus other second-line antidiabetic drugs (empagliflozin, dapagliflozin, sitagliptin) in the same population. Semaglutide still won. That matters, because it begins to rule out the explanation that patients simply feel better when their diabetes is better controlled by any means.</p>
  <p>The primary outcomes were deliberately severe: psychiatric hospitalization, sick leave exceeding 14 days, self-harm, suicide. The study found semaglutide associated with a 44% lower risk of worsening depression (aHR 0.56), a 38% lower risk of worsening anxiety disorder (aHR 0.62), and that 47% reduction in worsening substance use disorder (aHR 0.53). Overall worsening of mental illness was 42% lower. Dr. Hertzel Gerstein of McMaster University, commenting on the database itself, noted it contains "data on all Swedes from birth until death" — the kind of population-level completeness that makes epidemiologists quietly envious.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The revelation about GLP-1 medication is that it really works against all major substances... because it is likely acting against the craving itself. It blunts that craving that pulls people toward whatever they're addicted to." — Dr. Ziyad Al-Aly, Washington University in St. Louis</p></aside>

<section id="addiction-mechanism" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Reward Circuit, Interrupted</h2>
  <p>The substance use disorder finding is the most surprising result in the dataset. It is also, once you understand the neuroscience, the most mechanistically coherent. GLP-1 receptors are not confined to the pancreas and the hypothalamus, where the textbooks put them. They are expressed densely in the ventral tegmental area (VTA) and the nucleus accumbens (NAc) — the core architecture of the brain's reward circuit, the same circuitry that encodes craving, compulsion, and the anticipatory dopamine surge that precedes every relapse.</p>
  <p>When semaglutide activates those receptors, it modulates dopamine release and blunts the reward salience of addictive stimuli. Not for one substance. For all of them. A 2021 systematic review in <em>Frontiers in Neuroscience</em> (PMC) examining 30 clinical and 71 preclinical studies found GLP-1 agonists effective in reducing cocaine, amphetamine, alcohol, and nicotine use in animals, with GLP-1 modulating dopaminergic and glutamatergic neurotransmission as the operative mechanism. A WashU Medicine analysis of over 600,000 U.S. veterans with type 2 diabetes found GLP-1 use associated with seven fewer new cases of substance use disorder and 12 fewer harmful addiction-related events per 1,000 patients — effects consistent across alcohol, opioids, stimulants, cannabis, and nicotine simultaneously.</p>
  <p>That cross-substance consistency is the intellectual heart of this story. Dr. Ziyad Al-Aly, the clinical epidemiologist at Washington University who led the veterans analysis, put it plainly: "In addiction medicine, a lot of treatments target just one thing... The revelation about GLP-1 medication is that it really works against all major substances... because it is likely acting against the craving itself." The drug isn't blocking opioid receptors or substituting for alcohol. It's operating upstream, at the level of wanting itself.</p>
  <p>There is also a gut-brain pathway that deserves more than a footnote. GLP-1 is secreted by intestinal L-cells in response to food. It activates vagal afferents that project to the nucleus tractus solitarius, which sends glutamatergic projections into mesolimbic structures — a gut-to-reward-circuit highway that evolution built for satiety signaling and that semaglutide appears to be co-opting for something considerably more interesting. Dr. Carolina Haass-Koffler of Brown University's psychiatry department framed it this way: "GLP-1s aren't just targeting the brain, like many older medications. They work more holistically, helping the brain and the body." That holism is not a marketing phrase. It reflects a genuine convergence of metabolic and neural signaling that the field has underestimated.</p>
  <p>The first prospective RCT evidence arrived in 2025, when Christian Hendershot and colleagues at the USC Institute for Addiction Science published a randomized clinical trial in <em>JAMA Psychiatry</em> finding that low-dose once-weekly semaglutide reduced alcohol craving and some drinking outcomes in adults with alcohol use disorder. It was low-dose, short-term, and modest in effect size. It was not a cure. But it was a controlled experiment confirming that the observational signal has a real-world correlate — and Hendershot noted that "a slew of clinical trials already underway will give clearer answers over the next few years."</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Key Findings at a Glance: The Lancet Psychiatry Swedish Cohort (2026)</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Study population:</strong> 95,490 Swedish adults with pre-existing depression or anxiety</li>
    <li><strong>Design:</strong> Within-individual stratified Cox regression (on-drug vs. off-drug periods)</li>
    <li><strong>Overall mental illness worsening:</strong> 42% lower risk with semaglutide (vs. non-use)</li>
    <li><strong>Depression worsening:</strong> 44% lower risk (aHR 0.56)</li>
    <li><strong>Anxiety disorder worsening:</strong> 38% lower risk (aHR 0.62)</li>
    <li><strong>Substance use disorder worsening:</strong> 47% lower risk (aHR 0.53)</li>
    <li><strong>Liraglutide:</strong> 18% reduction in mental illness worsening — significant but substantially weaker</li>
    <li><strong>Exenatide / dulaglutide:</strong> No significant psychiatric effect detected</li>
    <li><strong>Comparator:</strong> Semaglutide outperformed empagliflozin, dapagliflozin, and sitagliptin head-to-head</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="potency-hierarchy" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Potency Ladder: Clue or Confound?</h2>
  <p>The dose-response pattern in the data is either the most compelling pharmacological clue in the entire dataset or its most dangerous confound. Possibly both. Semaglutide produces the largest psychiatric benefit. Liraglutide produces a real but substantially smaller one — 18% versus 42%. Exenatide and dulaglutide produce nothing detectable. This hierarchy mirrors almost exactly the drugs' relative potency for weight loss and glycemic control, and it mirrors their relative CNS penetration and receptor binding affinity. Semaglutide crosses the blood-brain barrier more readily. It binds GLP-1 receptors with greater affinity. If the psychiatric effect is genuinely pharmacological, you would expect exactly this gradient.</p>
  <p>But the confound is real and worth naming honestly. Semaglutide is the newest, most aggressively marketed, and most expensive drug in the class. Physicians prescribing it may be doing so for patients who are more motivated, more adherent, more engaged with their health — and those patients may be doing better psychiatrically for reasons that have nothing to do with the molecule. The within-individual design blunts this concern considerably, but it cannot eliminate it entirely. A patient who is actively managing their diabetes, attending appointments, and filling prescriptions is, in those same periods, doing something that correlates with better mental health outcomes. Lähteenvuo acknowledged this directly. The potency hierarchy is suggestive. It is not proof.</p>
  <p>Nora D. Volkow, writing in <em>Addiction</em> in 2024 with co-authors reviewing GLP-1 receptor agonists for addiction treatment, highlighted that GLP-1RAs appear to reduce neuroinflammation through central effects partly mediated via opioid receptors — a mechanism that would predict potency-dependent effects and that adds biological plausibility to the gradient. The neuroinflammation story matters independently: GLP-1 agonists inhibit NF-κB signaling, reduce pro-inflammatory cytokines including IL-1β, IL-6, and TNF-α, and attenuate NLRP3 inflammasome activation. Depression has a robust neuroinflammatory component. If semaglutide is suppressing that inflammation centrally, the mood effects may be partly metabolic and partly direct — and disentangling the two is going to require trials that haven't been run yet.</p>
</section>

<section id="counter-evidence" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Evidence That Doesn't Fit the Narrative</h2>
  <p>Here is where the story gets harder, and where it needs to stay hard. A 16-week double-blind randomized controlled trial of oral semaglutide in overweight and obese adults with major depressive disorder, published in <em>Med</em> (Cell Press) in 2026, found pro-cognitive effects but no significant impact on depressive symptom severity. Not a modest effect. No effect. In a controlled experiment, with a defined population, semaglutide did not move the needle on depression. That finding does not cancel the Swedish cohort data — the populations, doses, and outcome measures are different — but it is a serious check on the enthusiasm. The cognitive and mood pathways may be partially dissociable. The drug may be doing something real for craving and for cognition without being a direct antidepressant in the clinical sense.</p>
  <p>Then there is the VigiBase signal. A pharmacovigilance analysis published in 2025, drawing on over 2 million adverse event reports in the WHO's VigiBase database, found significant post-marketing signals for anxiety (adjusted reporting odds ratio 1.26), depressed mood disorders (aROR 1.70), and suicidality (aROR 1.45) with semaglutide — signals that intensified after the drug's approval for obesity management expanded its user base dramatically. The FDA added a warning about suicidal ideation and depression to GLP-1 labels in 2023.</p>
  <p>Pharmacovigilance data is not the same as the Lancet Psychiatry study. It is substantially weaker evidence. VigiBase captures spontaneous adverse event reports — a system that is notoriously susceptible to reporting bias, notoriety bias, and the absence of a denominator. You cannot calculate incidence from it. You cannot establish causality. The Swedish cohort, with its within-individual design and population-level completeness, is a more rigorous instrument by a considerable margin. Say so clearly. And then say this: an aROR of 1.70 for depressed mood disorders is not a rounding error. It is a signal in a dataset of 2 million reports, and it is telling us that some patients, in the real world, are getting worse. The population-level benefit and the individual-level harm can coexist. They probably do.</p>
  <p>There is also the biphasic anxiety response. Animal models show GLP-1 agonists can induce acute anxiety at treatment initiation before longer-term positive effects emerge. Some patients report worsening anxiety in the early weeks of treatment. Population-level data, which averages across time, may obscure this pattern entirely. A patient who deteriorates in week three and discontinues the drug before week twelve never appears in the long-term benefit statistics. The Swedish study's primary outcomes — hospitalization, extended sick leave, self-harm, suicide — capture only the most severe psychiatric deterioration. Milder worsening that doesn't reach clinical threshold is invisible to this instrument. That is not a flaw unique to this study. It is a limitation that matters when you are deciding whether to prescribe.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Because this is a registry-based study, we cannot determine exactly why or how these medications affect mood symptoms, but the association was quite strong." — Markku Lähteenvuo, MD, PhD, University of Eastern Finland</p></aside>

<section id="access-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>The $1,000-a-Month Question</h2>
  <p>The Swedish cohort study was conducted in a universal healthcare system where drug access is not determined by ability to pay. The study authors themselves noted that GLP-1 drug costs could restrict access to those who would most benefit. In the United States, semaglutide runs approximately $900 to $1,300 per month without insurance coverage. Medicaid coverage is inconsistent across states. Medicare only recently began covering GLP-1s for cardiovascular indications, not for psychiatric ones.</p>
  <p>If the psychiatric benefits of semaglutide are real — and the evidence is strong enough to take seriously — then the people most likely to benefit from them are also the people least likely to afford them. Substance use disorder disproportionately affects lower-income populations. Depression and anxiety are more prevalent and more severe in communities with less economic security. A drug that might reduce psychiatric hospitalization, self-harm, and addiction relapse at the population level is, at current pricing, a drug for people who already have better health outcomes. That is not a footnote. It is a structural problem that belongs in any honest accounting of what this research means in practice.</p>
  <p>The Epic Research dataset, drawn from approximately 4 million patients, showed semaglutide linked to reductions in the prevalence of anxiety and depression diagnoses at the population level. That population skews insured, employed, and urban. The 47% reduction in substance use disorder worsening from the Swedish cohort was measured in a country where the drug was accessible. Extrapolating that number to a U.S. context where access is rationed by income requires assumptions the data cannot support.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"GLP-1s aren't just targeting the brain, like many older medications. They work more holistically, helping the brain and the body." — Dr. Carolina Haass-Koffler, Brown University</p></aside>

<section id="implications" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Psychiatry Has to Reckon With</h2>
  <p>Rodrigo Mansur, a psychiatrist at the University of Toronto, hypothesized in 2015 — before GLP-1 drugs were approved for weight loss, before the obesity trials, before any of this — that GLP-1 drugs might help treat mental illness. His reasoning was mechanistic: the overlap in neural circuits governing metabolic regulation and mood. The 2026 Lancet Psychiatry data now substantially supports that prediction. That is worth pausing on. A hypothesis generated from circuit biology, a decade before the population data existed, turned out to be correct. That is how mechanistic reasoning is supposed to work, and it is a point in favor of taking the neuroscience seriously rather than waiting for every RCT to be completed before updating priors.</p>
  <p>The deeper provocation is this: if a single drug reduces depression, anxiety, and substance use disorder simultaneously — across different substances, in different populations, through a mechanism that operates on shared neural circuitry — then what does that say about the categorical distinctions psychiatry has built its diagnostic architecture around? The DSM treats major depressive disorder, generalized anxiety disorder, and alcohol use disorder as separate entities with separate etiologies requiring separate treatments. The semaglutide data suggests they may share, at some level, the same dysregulation in the same circuits. Reward system dysfunction. Neuroinflammation. Metabolic-psychiatric feedback loops. The same broken thermostat, expressed differently depending on genetics, environment, and history.</p>
  <p>A 2024 eClinicalMedicine study in propensity-score matched cohorts of approximately 65,000 patients found semaglutide not associated with increased neuropsychiatric risk and showing reduced risk of cognitive deficit (HR 0.72) and nicotine misuse compared to sitagliptin, glipizide, and empagliflozin. The cognitive finding is consistent with the 2026 MDD RCT's pro-cognitive result — and it suggests that whatever semaglutide is doing in the brain, it is doing something real and replicable, even if the antidepressant signal in controlled trials remains elusive.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">The Evidence Hierarchy: What We Know and How Well We Know It</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Strongest evidence:</strong> Swedish within-individual cohort (n=95,490, Lancet Psychiatry 2026) — large, well-designed, population-complete, but observational</li>
    <li><strong>Supporting observational:</strong> WashU veterans analysis (n=600,000+) — cross-substance SUD reduction; Epic Research (n=~4M) — population-level anxiety/depression prevalence reduction</li>
    <li><strong>RCT evidence (positive):</strong> Hendershot et al., JAMA Psychiatry 2025 — alcohol use disorder, low-dose, short-term, modest effect; first prospective controlled evidence</li>
    <li><strong>RCT evidence (null):</strong> Med (Cell Press) 2026 — oral semaglutide in MDD; no effect on depressive symptom severity at 16 weeks</li>
    <li><strong>Safety signal:</strong> VigiBase pharmacovigilance (2M+ reports, 2025) — aROR 1.45 suicidality, 1.70 depressed mood; weaker methodology, real-world signal</li>
    <li><strong>Preclinical/mechanistic:</strong> Systematic review, 30 clinical + 71 preclinical studies (PMC/Frontiers 2021) — GLP-1 modulation of dopamine and glutamate in reward circuits</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="closing" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Question the Trials Have to Answer</h2>
  <p>The trials now underway — Hendershot's group at USC, Volkow's collaborators at NIDA, multiple European centers — are asking whether semaglutide helps with addiction and mood disorders in controlled conditions. That is the right question to be asking. But it is not the only question, and it may not be the most important one. The more precise question, the one that will determine whether this drug becomes a psychiatric tool or a cautionary tale, is: which patients, at what dose, with what psychiatric history, and monitored by whom?</p>
  <p>The VigiBase suicidality signal tells us that some patients get worse. The biphasic anxiety response tells us that timing matters. The null MDD RCT tells us that the mechanism is not simply "more semaglutide equals better mood." The population-level benefit is real and large. The individual-level risk is real and currently unquantifiable. Those two facts are not in contradiction. They are the shape of a drug that is doing something genuinely complex in a system — the human brain — that we do not understand as well as we pretend to.</p>
  <p>What semaglutide has done, inadvertently, is hand psychiatry a probe. A molecule that reaches the VTA, the nucleus accumbens, the prefrontal cortex, and the hippocampus simultaneously, and that produces measurable changes in depression, anxiety, and addiction outcomes, is not just a treatment candidate. It is a research instrument. It is asking, with the bluntness of a 47% effect size, whether the categorical boundaries between metabolic disease and psychiatric disease were ever as clean as the diagnostic manuals implied. Whether metabolic medicine has been treating mental illness by accident for years — in every patient whose glycemic control improved, whose inflammation dropped, whose weight came down — and whether we simply lacked the data resolution to see it.</p>
    <p>The honest answer to whether semaglutide belongs in the psychiatric formulary is still two or three years away, contingent on trials that are adequately powered, long enough to capture the biphasic response, and designed to identify the patients for whom the drug makes things worse rather than better. That answer will be more complicated than the headlines currently suggest. It will probably be more interesting, too.</p>
</section>

